The 172nd Military Intelligence (MI) Company had a POW compound with 
the use of an attached squad of Vietnamese interpreter/interrogators.  Being mostly Southerners from around Saigon, they were often less fluent in the local dialect than I am in Australian "Strine".  Some of you may remember, back in 1970, Col. Anthony B. Herbert's allegations on "60 Minutes" of mistreatment of Viet Cong POWs.  This was the compound he was referring to.
<p>
Was interviewed by a CID* type from Washington in December '70 as to what I knew.  In intelligence, you keep things compartmentalized on a "need-to-know" basis. The interrogation people stayed out of my primitive deuce-and-a-half mounted photo developing and interpretation facilities, and I stayed out of the POW compound.  Only entered once in a year, for some reason I can no longer remember.  The only information I had about what went on there was from a source who often tried to say something outrageous just to get a rise from somebody.  You never knew when he was serious or joking.  The following; as I told the investigator; is unsubstantiated hearsay, or as we said in MI : F6 (unreliable, on a scale of A to F; unconfirmed, on a scale of 1 to 6):
<blockquote>
          	Supposedly, the prisoner was seated on a stool with a field
           	phone wired to his genitals.  (For the nonmilitary, a field phone
	had a crank that produced just enough electric current to operate 
	the phone.  Still would produce quite an unpleasant shock in a  
           	sensitive area of the body.) When an unsatisfactory answer
           	was given, one of the South Vietnamese interpreters would  
           	ring him up. 
</blockquote>
Am hoping that no one will be able to verify a similar story, though I believe something like this is quite possible and probable.  Have heard many second- and third-hand stories of "toss the prisoner overboard" incidents, often from parties--the ones with the "kill 'em all and let God sort 'em out" T- shirts--who claim to approve of it.  My views to the contrary aren't always welcome.  But I wonder what they say in their hearts at those times--which get  more frequent as we get older--when they have to face their own mortality. 
<p>
Gerald A. Ney<br>
