This is Lou Grivetti...
<p>
Last night in seminar one of the speakers confirmed that he had seen interrogation techniques where one or more persons was tossed out of a helicopter in order to get someone to talk. This is part of the aftermath of war, the images, the thought of interrogation by execution.
<p>
What did the young man think as downward he fell, accelerating at 32 feet per second, per second?  Did he recall the exploits of his military unit?  Did he remember the names of friends who slipped away under cover of night who evaded capture by ARVN* and US forces? What did the young man think as he twisted and tumbled downward through the sky? Did he hold the vision of a loved one dear, as Mother Earth reached up and gathered him to her bosom?
<p>
What were the thoughts of the American soldier in the helicopter flying parallel at the moment of the deed, he who took the photograph and captured for posterity the atrocity on film?  Did the young American shout out-- NO--before the camera clicked and preserved forever the evidence of the crime?
<p>
Who was this youth inside the photograph falling earthward, blindfolded, hands bound behind his back, who had not spoken to his interrogators? Who, because of his silence, suffered this unkind fate?
<p>
Photographer... what story did you tell that night when off duty, you and your buddies went to drink in the NCO lounge?
<p>
Interrogator... what story did you tell that night when off duty, you and your buddies drank scotch in the officers' lounge?
<p>
Mother... did you wake from your nap that dark afternoon at the moment of your son's terrible death?
<p>
Sister... did you stir in pain, sensing the death of your brother as you bent to cut a bunch of rice?
<p>
Down...down... he fell until gathered, caressed, and engulfed by the rippling, billowing waves of the rice field.
<p>
Down...down...  falling until he struck Mother Earth and his crumpled, crushed body stained the green tufts of nourishment.
<p>
His soul set free he took his place among the roster of the dead, among the souls of thousands, countless thousands of others--more than two million--who died needlessly.
<p>
Interrogator... twenty five years later do you remember your thoughts and actions as you pushed the youth out of the helicopter to certain death below?
<p>
Photographer... twenty five years later do you remember your thoughts and actions as you snapped the shutter of your camera and witnessed the youth's fall to certain death below?
<p>
View the evidence and remember.
<p>
This image is what continues to haunt me.....
<p>
