I asked my ex-husband what he thought about the issue of throwing interrogation subjects out of helicopters, and he sent me a very thoughtful reply. He was an interrogator with Military Intelligence in An Khe (near DaNang), 1970-71. He gave me permission to forward part of his reply to this list.  He writes:
<p>
I never saw it happen, never did it myself, never knew of a confirmed 
case of it happening, but heard often about it happening as something 
that used to happen quite often.  I think it is the military equivalent of an 
urban legend.  But who knows--the mere existence such legends can give 
people the authority to enact them.  And I was only there the year I was 
there, toward the end of a 10-year war.  But I certainly never met an 
interrogator who had done so, and I knew a lot of them.  
<p>
The simplest reason not to do it, and one I'm sure your discussion group
never thought of, is that it would generate a paperwork nightmare--the 
interrogator, and the accompanying combat MP* have signed for the guy, 
and have to return him to someone else, who also signs for him.  It works 
exactly like a detective taking a prisoner out of a cell to an interrogation 
room in a police station, except that a POW has more protection, legal and 
actual, than a criminal suspect has, because the MP's only interest is the 
safety and well-being of the prisoner--he doesn't give a fuck whether you 
succeed in your job or not.  Anyway, there wasn't any space on the form for
"lost him," or "dropped him," or "tortured him to death."  You returned him, 
or faced court martial.
<p>
On the other hand, prisoners were often threatened this way, always
by implication.  The other side knew the legend too, you see.
They turned pale when they realized you were going to take them up in
a helicopter.
<p>
I've done that, a number of times.  A cooperative helicopter
pilot helps, by making the helicopter do weird things, which are safe
(by combat standards) but very scary.  I suppose maybe someone lost
somebody that way once, but I doubt it.  I've lain on the floor of a helicopter
with my head sticking out, beside a POW, with the floor at 89 degrees to 
the ground, the G-forces being only thing keeping you in.  You make the 
wrong move in a situation like that and you can fall out, although it's harder 
to do than one might think.  This is of course absolutely terrifying for 
someone who has never flown before in any way.  This is also why you don't 
threaten them with throwing them out.  That is stupid.  It is much more
effective to let them worry about whether you will make that threat,
or simply let them succumb to the terror of flying, a common terror even
among those who fly a lot.
<p>
Also, if you make a threat, your bluff might be called.  People
usually can get their guts together to die to call someone's bluff.
And then you either back down, or don't get your information, because
you have to kill the guy, or the next one.  Interrogators never threaten, never 
bluff.  You lead the prisoner to do that for you.  You help the prisoner to 
scare himself.    
<p>
Anyway, the pilot tilts the chopper, to ostensibly provide a better
view of what you want the prisoner to show you.  (One tells the
prisoner this, before it happens.  Anticipation makes it worse. 
You are pretending to warn them so they "won't be afraid."  And,
I affirm, it is a very unsettling feeling to be standing on your head
1000 feet off the ground, even if you're used to it.) 
<p>
In the usual military way, the cool of the interrogator was being tested, too.
Pilots of Cavalry choppers, an enormously dangerous job, had no
patience with interrogators who had uneasy stomachs.  Nowadays I'd
probably fall out myself, but then it was fun.
<p>
Most "interrogation stories", including the one about throwing people from
helicopters, clearly betray an absolute lack of  knowledge about how 
people are actually induced to talk; it is quite clear that they are just the 
fantasies of people who know absolutely nothing about the business.  
They assume that a person can be induced to talk because of the death of 
another person, or by threats of death to themselves, or by physical abuse.  
People can and do resist these things.  We know they can because of the
way our own POWs in Viet Nam resisted them.
<p>
When you think about it, thinking that people are generally
susceptible to threats and violence is really dumb.
All combat soldiers know that death is a distinct possibility, and make
their peace with it.  People are induced to talk by putting them in a
position of imagining whatever it is that they actually fear.
<p>
Americans, as always, assume that Vietnamese are
somehow more cowardly than they are--simple racism.  Americans can 
never be got to believe that others could behave just like
we would.  
<p>
The less kind way to interpret both the interrogation
story is to say that Americans are cowards at heart,
and therefore believe that others are, too.  But I don't think this is the case;
I think Americans are just racists and nationalists.
<p>
[care of]<br>
